    "Figure1shows an example of the tag extracted from training data (220-05.xml) in both versions, together with its evidence in the text field.",
    "Table 22A summary of the shared task dataset's risk factor tagsAnnotation-level training and testing set sizes, as well as indicators for each heart risk factorRisk factor tagsIndicatorTimeBefore DCTDuring DCTAfter DCT(a) Tag: CAD IndicatorMention260261 Event22420 Symptom5424(b) Tag: Diabetes indicatorMention518524 Glucose169A1C8921(c) Tag: Hyperlipdemia indicatorHigh LDL2310 High chol.51Mention340340(d) Tag: Hypertension indicatorHigh bp41322 Mention523521(e) Tag: Obese indicatorDMI315Mention133147(f) Tag: Medication type (type1)Thienopyridine9798 Statin436427 Thiazolidinedione4341 Aspirin4246 Metformin187176 Insulin204218 Fibrate2220 Ezetimibe1212 Diuretic11399 Anti diabetes11ARB9893 Sulfonylureas159155 DPP4 inhibitors10ACE inhibitor326318(g) Tag: Family_history indicatorNot presentNANAPresent(g) Tag: Smoker statusCurrentNANAEverNeverPastUnknown Table 55BERT evaluation metrics for each risk factor indicatorBold indicates the best value Table 66RoBERTa Evaluation Metrics for each risk factor indicatorThe numerical results of a laboratory must be extracted accurately.",
    "After the proposed model has found the matching terms for laboratory or test indicators, the model must extract the numerical values associated with those terms and compare them with threshold levels that indicate an abnormality.",
    "When the numbers follow the term and are expressed as a single unit, like in 'GLU 230(H)', it may be easy to extract them.",
    "There are, however, some phrases that may be more difficult to detect, such as 'FS in the AM ∼ 90-180'; now 80-175, mostly 90-180'."
